  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What were the most important events happened in India in 2016?",
  "response": "In 2016, several significant events took place in India that had profound impacts on its political, social, and economic landscape. Here are some of the most important events:\n\n1. **Demonetization (November 8, 2016)**:\n   - Prime Minister Narendra Modi announced the demonetization of \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 currency notes in an effort to curb black money, corruption, and counterfeit currency. This move led to widespread cash shortages, economic disruption, and significant public debate.\n\n2. **Surgical Strikes across the Line of Control (September 29, 2016)**:\n   - In response to a terrorist attack on an Indian Army base in Uri, Jammu and Kashmir, the Indian Army conducted surgical strikes against terrorist launch pads across the Line of Control (LoC) in Pakistan-administered Kashmir. This marked a significant shift in India's approach to cross-border terrorism.\n\n3. **India\u2019s Entry into the Missile Technology Control Regime (June 27, 2016)**:\n   - India became a member of the Missile Technology Control Regime (MTCR), a key multilateral export control regime. This was a significant step in India's integration into the global non-proliferation architecture.\n\n4. **Launch of the Goods and Services Tax (GST) Bill (August 3, 2016)**:\n   - The Indian Parliament passed the Goods and Services Tax (GST) Bill, which aimed to create a unified tax structure across the country. The GST was subsequently implemented on July 1, 2017, but the legislative process in 2016 was a crucial milestone.\n\n5. **Haryana Jat Reservation Agitation (February 2016)**:\n   - The Jat community in Haryana launched widespread protests demanding reservation in government jobs and educational institutions under the Other Backward Classes (OBC) category. The agitation led to significant violence, property damage, and disruption of essential services.\n\n6. **Maratha Silent Marches (July-August 2016)**:\n   - The Maratha community in Maharashtra organized large-scale silent marches to demand reservations in education and jobs, as well as to protest against the Kopardi rape case. These marches highlighted issues of caste and social justice.\n\n7. **Kerala Floods (July-August 2016)**:\n   - Kerala experienced severe floods due to unprecedented monsoon rains, leading to significant loss of life, property, and infrastructure. The floods highlighted the need for better disaster management strategies.\n\n8. **India\u2019s First All-Woman Crew Flight by Air India (March 6, 2016)**:\n   - Air India operated its first all-woman crew flight from Delhi to San Francisco, marking a significant milestone in the aviation industry and promoting gender equality.\n\n9. **Arunachal Pradesh Political Crisis (January-February 2016)**:\n   - A political crisis unfolded in Arunachal Pradesh, leading to the imposition of President's Rule and subsequent legal battles. The Supreme Court\u2019s intervention ultimately reinstated the Congress-led government.\n\n10. **Hyderabad University Student Protests (January 2016)**:\n    - Protests erupted at the University of Hyderabad following the suicide of Dalit scholar Rohith Vemula. The incident sparked nationwide outrage and discussions on caste discrimination and social justice in educational institutions.\n\nThese events collectively shaped the political, economic, and social fabric of India in 2016, leaving a lasting impact on the country's trajectory.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
